---
title: 03 varints
---

Q: What does each LEB128 uvarint byte contain?
A: 7 payload bits plus high-bit continuation flag.

---

Q: What is the group order for protobuf uvarint?
A: Least-significant 7-bit group first.

---

Q: Encode 0 as uvarint.
A: `00`.

---

Q: Encode 127 and 128 as uvarints.
A: `127 -> 7f`; `128 -> 80 01`.

---

Q: Encode 300 as uvarint.
A: `ac 02`.

---

Q: Encode 16384 as uvarint.
A: `80 80 01`.

---

Q: Max encoded length for u32 and u64 uvarints.
A: u32: 5 bytes. u64: 10 bytes.

---

Q: What can the 10th byte of a u64 uvarint contribute?
A: Only payload bit 0; any higher payload bit overflows u64.

---

Q: Why must the encode loop emit before testing for exit?
A: Because `0` must emit one byte, `00`.

---

Q: Streaming uvarint decoder state.
A: `(accumulator, shift, byte_count)`.

---

Q: What is `80` by itself?
A: Truncated: a valid prefix needing more bytes.

---

Q: What is `80 00`?
A: Overlong encoding of 0.

---

Q: What is `80` x10 then `01`?
A: Too long for u64; an 11th group would be required.

---

Q: What is the C cast needed in varint decode?
A: `(uint64_t)(b & 0x7f) << shift`.

---

Q: Why does negative input break a Python uvarint encode loop?
A: Right-shifting a negative approaches `-1`, so `while n` may never terminate.

---

Q: Zigzag map for `-2`, `-1`, `0`, `1`, `2`.
A: `3`, `1`, `0`, `2`, `4`.

---

Q: Python zigzag encode at i64.
A: `((n << 1) ^ (n >> 63)) & ((1 << 64) - 1)`.

---

Q: Python zigzag decode.
A: `(u >> 1) ^ -(u & 1)`.

---

Q: Why does protobuf `int64 -1` take 10 bytes?
A: It stores raw two's-complement as u64, so `-1` becomes `2^64 - 1`.

---

Q: In protobuf, what is the field key varint?
A: `(field_number << 3) | wire_type`.
